  <h2>Understanding Rose wine</h2>

  <h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Rosé wine's origins trace back to ancient civilizations, making it one of the world's oldest wine styles—predating both modern red and white winemaking techniques by millennia. Archaeological evidence suggests that the first wines produced in regions like <strong>Georgia, Armenia, and the eastern Mediterranean</strong> around 6000 BCE were naturally rosé in color, as ancient winemakers lacked the knowledge to extract deep color from grape skins.</p>

<h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Rosé wine's origins stretch back to antiquity, making it arguably the world's oldest wine style. The ancient Greeks and Romans produced what we now call rosé by default—their winemaking techniques naturally resulted in pale pink wines since they lacked the knowledge to extract deep color from red grape skins. Archaeological evidence from <strong>6000 BCE</strong> suggests that the first wines produced in regions like Georgia and Armenia were likely rosé-colored due to minimal skin contact during fermentation.</p>

<p>The modern concept of intentional rosé production emerged in <strong>Provence, France</strong>, where winemakers began perfecting the <em>saignée</em> method during the medieval period. The region's gravelly soils and Mediterranean climate proved ideal for producing the pale, dry rosés that would become the global standard. The name "rosé" itself derives from the French word for pink, though the style was historically called "clairet" in Bordeaux, giving rise to the English term "claret."</p>

<h3>The Provence Revolution</h3>

<p>Provence's reputation was cemented in the 19th century when wealthy Parisians began vacationing along the French Riviera, demanding the local pale pink wines. Estates like <strong>Château d'Esclans</strong> and <strong>Domaine Ott</strong> elevated rosé from a rustic country wine to a luxury product, pioneering temperature-controlled fermentation and protective winemaking techniques that preserved the wine's delicate aromatics.</p>

<h3>Global Renaissance</h3>

<p>The 21st century has witnessed an unprecedented rosé renaissance. Global consumption has increased by over <strong>40% since 2010</strong>, with France leading production at 28% of world output, followed by Spain (18%) and the United States (11%). The #RoséAllDay movement, amplified by social media, transformed rosé from a seasonal sipper to a year-round phenomenon.</p>

<p>Today's rosé landscape spans from <strong>Bandol's structured Mourvèdre-based wines</strong> to <strong>California's fruit-forward Pinot Noir rosés</strong> and <strong>Spain's crisp Garnacha interpretations</strong>. This diversity reflects rosé's adaptability—virtually any red grape variety can produce exceptional rosé when handled with proper technique, making it one of the most globally democratic wine styles.</p>

<h2>Grape Characteristics & Winemaking</h2>

<div class="bg-wine-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
