  <li><strong>Judge Quality by Color Intensity, Not Darkness</strong> - Contrary to popular belief, deeper pink rosés aren't necessarily better. Premium Provence rosés like Domaine Tempier showcase pale salmon hues from gentle pressing, while darker rosés often indicate longer skin contact or lower-quality grapes. Look for clarity and vibrancy rather than saturation—the best rosés have a crystal-clear appearance with brilliant color that catches light beautifully.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at 45-50°F, Not Ice-Cold</strong> - Most people over-chill rosé, masking its delicate aromatics and fruit complexity. The ideal serving temperature is slightly warmer than standard white wine service. At 45-50°F, you'll taste the subtle strawberry and white peach notes in a Côtes de Provence, while ice-cold temperatures mute these nuances and emphasize only acidity and minerality.</li>

  <li><strong>Never Decant Rosé—It Destroys the Magic</strong> - Rosé's charm lies in its fresh, ephemeral character and delicate aromatics that dissipate quickly with aeration. Unlike reds that benefit from oxygen exposure, rosé should go straight from bottle to glass. Even swirling should be minimal—a gentle rotation is enough to release those fleeting notes of rose petals and citrus zest.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Tulip-Shaped Glasses Over Flutes</strong> - While many serve rosé in flutes, a tulip-shaped white wine glass with a slightly narrower rim concentrates the delicate aromatics better. The bowl should be large enough to accommodate gentle swirling but tapered to funnel those subtle scents of wild herbs and red berries directly to your nose, enhancing the overall tasting experience.</li>

